- 'shining stars' refers to books that perform well in both sales and ratings;
- 'in the eyes of the readers' refers to the average rating of the books;
- 'in the ledger of sales' refers to the average revenue from each sale;
- 'financial success' is determined by the average sales revenue;
- 'critical acclaim' is determined by the average rating.

- 'total revenue' and 'total sales' are key indicators of commercial success in the publishing industry;
- 'average ratings' reflect the readers' satisfaction and quality perception of books in a genre;
- 'awards received' signify the recognition and prestige of publishers in the literary world.

- "gem, when its pages are turned and its stories are shared" refers to a book that has been sold;
- "shone the brightest in the marketplace, generating the most revenue" refers to the book with the highest total revenue;
- "leaving a lasting impact on readers and critics alike" refers to the book's ratings and awards.

- 'cumulative wealth' refers to the running total of the total revenue from book sales;
- 'literary treasures' refers to the books in the database;
- 'earnings' refers to the total revenue from the sale of each book.

- "shining stars" refers to the top-rated books in each genre;
- "collective wisdom of readers' ratings" refers to the average rating of the books;
- "volume of their reviews" refers to the number of reviews each book has received.

- 'Penguin' and 'HarperCollins' are well-known publishing companies;
- The number of awards won by a book can influence its popularity and sales;
- Total sales revenue is a measure of the financial success of a book.

- "best-selling" refers to the highest total revenue generated from sales;
- "success" is measured by the total revenue;
- "top 10" means the first 10 entries in the result set.
